- ♪ Sha la, la, la
- Sha la, la, la, la ♪

32
00:01:40,893 --> 00:01:46,002
♪ Sha la, la, la, la, la

33
00:01:50,282 --> 00:01:53,699
♪

34
00:01:53,734 --> 00:01:56,461
New York City, where I live.

35
00:01:56,495 --> 00:01:58,359
And it's easy to think,

36
00:01:58,394 --> 00:01:59,981
having lived here
nearly all my life,

37
00:02:00,016 --> 00:02:03,192
that this what America
looks like, thinks like,

38
00:02:03,226 --> 00:02:05,366
that the things that
are important to me

39
00:02:05,401 --> 00:02:06,885
are important to everybody.

40
00:02:06,919 --> 00:02:09,888
That anyplace else
is "out there."

41
00:02:09,922 --> 00:02:11,269
Unthinkable.

42
00:02:11,303 --> 00:02:13,823
Maybe even unknowable.

43
00:02:13,857 --> 00:02:14,357
♪

44
00:02:28,838 --> 00:02:31,668
600 miles away from
Midtown Manhattan

45
00:02:31,703 --> 00:02:34,326
is McDowell County,
West Virginia.

46
00:02:34,361 --> 00:02:35,983
Another America.

47
00:02:36,017 --> 00:02:38,537
In the mind of many
of my fellow New Yorkers,

48
00:02:38,572 --> 00:02:41,678
the heart of God,
guns and Trump country.

49
00:02:41,713 --> 00:02:44,336
The existential enemy.

50
00:02:47,374 --> 00:02:49,238
♪

51
00:02:49,272 --> 00:02:55,105
♪ There is a place
on God's creation ♪

52
00:02:55,140 --> 00:03:00,110
♪ A place of beauty
beyond compare ♪

53
00:03:00,145 --> 00:03:06,116
♪ Some people say
it's almost heaven ♪

54
00:03:06,151 --> 00:03:10,880
♪ Look for me
and you'll find me there ♪

55
00:03:10,914 --> 00:03:12,847
My daddy always told me,
you know,

56
00:03:12,882 --> 00:03:15,954
those tornados and hurricanes,
they can't get to us.

57
00:03:15,988 --> 00:03:18,405
We're way down in these
mountains, down in the holler,

58
00:03:18,439 --> 00:03:20,269
and these mountains protect us.

59
00:03:20,303 --> 00:03:23,789
Here, if you gonna see the sky,
you got to look up.

60
00:03:23,824 --> 00:03:27,759
♪ You can find me
on the highest mountain ♪

61
00:03:29,243 --> 00:03:34,041
♪ You can find me
in the black coal mines ♪

62
00:03:34,075 --> 00:03:36,388
To think about,
much less emphasize,

63
00:03:36,423 --> 00:03:37,700
with somebody who comes from

64
00:03:37,734 --> 00:03:39,633
five generations of coal miners

65
00:03:39,667 --> 00:03:41,807
in a place that looks like this

66
00:03:41,842 --> 00:03:44,879
is, to our enduring shame,
unthinkable.

67
00:03:44,914 --> 00:03:47,261
Why can't these coal miners
get retrained?

68
00:03:47,296 --> 00:03:50,091
Maybe put up solar panels
for a living.

69
00:03:50,126 --> 00:03:52,887
Why would these conservative,
deeply religious people

70
00:03:52,922 --> 00:03:56,477
vote for a thrice married
billionaire New Yorker?

71
00:03:56,512 --> 00:04:02,276
Well, I went to West Virginia
and, you know what, screw you.

72
00:04:04,036 --> 00:04:06,107
Here, in the heart
of every belief system

73
00:04:06,142 --> 00:04:08,109
I've ever mocked
or fought against,

74
00:04:08,144 --> 00:04:10,974
I was welcomed with
open arms by everyone.

75
00:04:11,009 --> 00:04:14,806
I found a place both
heartbreaking and beautiful,

76
00:04:14,840 --> 00:04:18,913
a place that symbolizes
and contains everything wrong

77
00:04:18,948 --> 00:04:23,470
and everything wonderful
and hopeful about America.

78
00:04:26,231 --> 00:04:27,750
The town of Welch,

79
00:04:27,784 --> 00:04:30,994
known in its glory days
as little New York.

80
00:04:31,029 --> 00:04:31,529
♪

81
00:04:37,829 --> 00:04:39,589
Welch is a very rural area.

82
00:04:39,624 --> 00:04:43,110
I mean, it's an hour
away from Walmart,

83
00:04:43,144 --> 00:04:45,215
I mean, if that
tells you anything.

84
00:04:45,250 --> 00:04:48,978
It's a real old, historic
town built in the 1800s.

85
00:04:49,012 --> 00:04:51,325
The American dream in miniature.

86
00:04:51,360 --> 00:04:54,535
A place where generations
of immigrants and dreamers

87
00:04:54,570 --> 00:04:56,882
could work
and lift up their family.

88
00:04:56,917 --> 00:04:59,540
The town of Welch,
when it was booming,

89
00:04:59,575 --> 00:05:01,853
the sidewalks were so crowded

90
00:05:01,887 --> 00:05:05,166
there would be traffic
backed up, like, a mile.

91
00:05:05,201 --> 00:05:08,238
You couldn't find
a place to park.

92
00:05:08,273 --> 00:05:12,035
We had three hospitals,
had the taxicab stand,

93
00:05:12,070 --> 00:05:14,659
had, like, three jewelry stores.

94
00:05:14,693 --> 00:05:16,488
It was just a wonderful place.

95
00:05:16,523 --> 00:05:18,801
The rest of the country
took a lot of money

96
00:05:18,835 --> 00:05:21,044
out of these hills
over the decades,

97
00:05:21,079 --> 00:05:23,702
billions and billions
of dollars,

98
00:05:23,737 --> 00:05:25,635
and when it became cheaper
or more convenient

99
00:05:25,670 --> 00:05:28,845
to pull the coal we needed
to power our electrical grids

100
00:05:28,880 --> 00:05:31,883
and to make our steel elsewhere,

101
00:05:31,917 --> 00:05:34,126
this is what was left behind.

102
00:05:38,130 --> 00:05:40,409
But this is not
a poverty porn show.

103
00:05:40,443 --> 00:05:42,272
Do not pity the people here,

104
00:05:42,307 --> 00:05:43,929
who, despite what you may think,

105
00:05:43,964 --> 00:05:46,932
are not unrealistic
about a return

106
00:05:46,967 --> 00:05:49,728
to the glory days of coal
and better times.

107
00:05:49,763 --> 00:05:52,179
I drank coffee from the time
I could walk.

108
00:05:52,213 --> 00:05:55,078
They put coffee in your bottle,
coffee or wine.

109
00:05:56,977 --> 00:05:59,393
Linda McKinney is a true
daughter of Appalachia.

110
00:05:59,428 --> 00:06:01,119
She raised her children here.

111
00:06:01,153 --> 00:06:02,879
Linda's husband, Bob McKinney,

112
00:06:02,914 --> 00:06:05,123
is a longtime
mine safety inspector.

113
00:06:05,157 --> 00:06:07,263
Now, your family's
originally from Naples?

114
00:06:07,297 --> 00:06:09,299
Is that right? Naples area?
Yes. Yes.

115
00:06:09,334 --> 00:06:11,232
Came here in 1923

116
00:06:11,267 --> 00:06:12,779
trying to strike it rich
in the coal mines.

117
00:06:12,786 --> 00:06:15,616
My mother died when I was five,

118
00:06:15,651 --> 00:06:17,515
so we went to live
with my nonna,

119
00:06:17,549 --> 00:06:18,895
and the first day I was there,

120
00:06:18,930 --> 00:06:20,690
she pulled me up
to a cook stove.

121
00:06:20,725 --> 00:06:23,037
This is the dish
that my nonna cooked

122
00:06:23,072 --> 00:06:25,971
during hunting season
with squirrels.

123
00:06:26,006 --> 00:06:29,699
These aren't squirrels.
This is chicken.

124
00:06:29,734 --> 00:06:31,977
Dinner is a not untypical
expression

125
00:06:32,012 --> 00:06:34,635
of hardscrabble
Appalachian practicality...

126
00:06:34,670 --> 00:06:36,810
Now, I don't measure anything,

127
00:06:36,844 --> 00:06:38,467
so nothing has a recipe here.

128
00:06:38,501 --> 00:06:40,469
- And Neapolitan roots.
- Basil.

129
00:06:40,503 --> 00:06:43,644
Home kitchen gardens,
hunting, and gathering.

130
00:06:43,679 --> 00:06:46,440
This my dad would call
piselles; it's peas.

131
00:06:46,475 --> 00:06:48,338
Ooh, making mama dance.

132
00:06:50,824 --> 00:06:53,585
Now, this is what I'm famous
for in these parts.

133
00:06:53,620 --> 00:06:55,587
Have you ever had
spaghetti pizza?

134
00:06:55,622 --> 00:06:56,588
- Wow.
- No, you haven't.

135
00:06:56,623 --> 00:06:57,624
Don't say you have.

136
00:07:00,868 --> 00:07:02,594
The tomato sauce was made

137
00:07:02,629 --> 00:07:04,665
with Joel's tomatoes
at the food bank.

138
00:07:04,700 --> 00:07:06,253
We harvested those yesterday,

139
00:07:06,287 --> 00:07:07,944
and I made spaghetti sauce.
Wow.

140
00:07:07,979 --> 00:07:10,360
Nearby, Joel runs an organic

141
00:07:10,395 --> 00:07:13,605
hydroponic farm that supplies
the local school system.

142
00:07:17,229 --> 00:07:18,990
The people here are very good.

143
00:07:19,024 --> 00:07:20,750
They'd give you the shirt
off their back,

144
00:07:20,785 --> 00:07:24,961
come together in times
of tragedy or anything.

145
00:07:24,996 --> 00:07:27,274
Christian values mean
something here.

146
00:07:27,308 --> 00:07:30,035
They're practiced
on the street and in the home.

147
00:07:30,070 --> 00:07:33,349
Most of you have all got
your potatoes, right?

148
00:07:33,383 --> 00:07:36,007
Linda runs Five Loaves
and Two Fishes,

149
00:07:36,041 --> 00:07:37,836
a food bank that holds
many of the lives here

150
00:07:37,871 --> 00:07:40,218
together during tough times.

151
00:07:40,252 --> 00:07:43,842
16,000 people walk through
these doors annually

152
00:07:43,877 --> 00:07:46,155
in a county of 20,000.

153
00:07:46,189 --> 00:07:48,813
Gracious God, we just
thank you for this day

154
00:07:48,847 --> 00:07:50,711
that we're able to
give food out again.

155
00:07:50,746 --> 00:07:52,817
This is not a regular give out.

156
00:07:52,851 --> 00:07:54,784
Watch over us. Protect us.

157
00:07:54,819 --> 00:07:57,304
Help us to keep cool heads.

158
00:08:00,341 --> 00:08:00,841
♪

159
00:08:04,656 --> 00:08:06,727
Father, we pray over
the food we're about to eat

160
00:08:06,762 --> 00:08:08,211
for the nourishment of our body.

161
00:08:08,246 --> 00:08:09,972
Just bless it
in the name of Christ.

162
00:08:10,006 --> 00:08:12,146
- Amen.
- Amen.

163
00:08:12,181 --> 00:08:12,681
♪

164
00:08:16,392 --> 00:08:18,843
This is our home.
We love it here.

165
00:08:18,877 --> 00:08:20,430
We're very close to our church.

166
00:08:20,465 --> 00:08:21,535
Everybody knows everybody.

167
00:08:21,570 --> 00:08:23,019
They're all dying now,

168
00:08:23,054 --> 00:08:24,883
but we're still hanging on,
aren't we, honey?

169
00:08:24,918 --> 00:08:26,920
Yeah.

170
00:08:26,954 --> 00:08:28,542
Was there any sizable

171
00:08:28,577 --> 00:08:30,544
Italian-American community
here at some time?

172
00:08:30,579 --> 00:08:32,270
Oh, yes. Oh, yes.

173
00:08:32,304 --> 00:08:34,755
A lot of immigrants from
different countries came here.

174
00:08:34,790 --> 00:08:36,446
- Still? How large?
- No.

175
00:08:36,481 --> 00:08:38,034
We've gone from what,
100,000 to 10,000.

176
00:08:38,069 --> 00:08:39,588
100,000 down to about
10,000-12,000.

177
00:08:39,622 --> 00:08:42,694
In the county itself,
as of the last census, so.

178
00:08:42,729 --> 00:08:44,696
Those are some grim statistics.

179
00:08:44,731 --> 00:08:46,456
Yes, yes.

180
00:08:46,491 --> 00:08:50,012
The coal that came out of
this area built America, right?

181
00:08:50,046 --> 00:08:51,185
Yes.

182
00:08:51,220 --> 00:08:52,490
McDowell County alone was called

183
00:08:52,497 --> 00:08:54,016
a billion-dollar coal field,

184
00:08:54,050 --> 00:08:57,226
and the people that were
in charge at the time

185
00:08:57,260 --> 00:08:59,918
didn't take advantage
of all that money

186
00:08:59,953 --> 00:09:02,472
in case something did happen
to the coal mine.

187
00:09:02,507 --> 00:09:04,854
The cool thing is that West
Virginia's developing

188
00:09:04,889 --> 00:09:07,961
a strong entrepreneur movement

189
00:09:07,995 --> 00:09:09,928
that a lot of people
don't know about.

190
00:09:09,963 --> 00:09:12,448
Like with Joe, he started
a hydroponic growing.

191
00:09:12,482 --> 00:09:14,726
I mean, not blaming others
for their problems,

192
00:09:14,761 --> 00:09:16,486
just trying to solve their own.

193
00:09:16,521 --> 00:09:19,420
A lot of people that's
really doing a lot of good

194
00:09:19,455 --> 00:09:21,491
that we don't hear about.

195
00:09:21,526 --> 00:09:22,907
This is our pumpkin pie cake.

196
00:09:22,941 --> 00:09:24,633
Have you ever had
a pumpkin pie cake?

197
00:09:24,667 --> 00:09:27,394
You probably won't like it,
so we'll take your spot.

198
00:09:29,189 --> 00:09:32,951
We got spoiled. The last
coal mines I worked at, I made-

199
00:09:32,986 --> 00:09:36,299
base salary was $94,000 a year.

200
00:09:36,334 --> 00:09:38,060
I also taught vocational school,

201
00:09:38,094 --> 00:09:39,751
and most of the kids
that I had said,

202
00:09:39,786 --> 00:09:40,959
"Well, I don't need this.

203
00:09:40,994 --> 00:09:42,271
I'm gonna go in the coal
mines."

204
00:09:42,305 --> 00:09:44,169
There's just
an education piece there

205
00:09:44,204 --> 00:09:46,344
now that we're trying to
instill in some of the people

206
00:09:46,378 --> 00:09:49,658
that still have that mentality
that coal was king,

207
00:09:49,692 --> 00:09:51,660
and, you know,
we don't doubt that,

208
00:09:51,694 --> 00:09:55,525
but we try to think outside the
box and look at some other...

209
00:09:55,560 --> 00:09:58,149
Some other opportunities
that might be there.

210
00:10:01,152 --> 00:10:02,671
The job that I have right now

211
00:10:02,705 --> 00:10:04,534
is probably one of
the best jobs around here

212
00:10:04,569 --> 00:10:08,677
other than the few guys
that works at the coal mines.

213
00:10:08,711 --> 00:10:10,851
I operate this school bus.

214
00:10:13,889 --> 00:10:16,132
♪

215
00:10:16,167 --> 00:10:19,653
I mentioned God,
and guns, and Trump.

216
00:10:19,688 --> 00:10:20,861
Get more physical!

217
00:10:20,896 --> 00:10:23,105
Let's go. Run!

218
00:10:23,139 --> 00:10:26,384
- But I forgot another
big one: football.

219
00:10:26,418 --> 00:10:29,318
I was born and raised here.
I've been here all my life.

220
00:10:29,352 --> 00:10:30,899
Played defensive end
for Welch High School.

221
00:10:30,906 --> 00:10:33,149
Graduated there in 1976.

222
00:10:33,184 --> 00:10:35,324
The Mountview Golden Knights
have long carried

223
00:10:35,358 --> 00:10:38,223
the mantle of the town
as perpetual underdogs.

224
00:10:38,258 --> 00:10:40,501
Mostly the children of miners,

225
00:10:40,536 --> 00:10:43,056
many from very difficult
situations at home.

226
00:10:43,090 --> 00:10:45,058
Why you walking? Hurry up!

227
00:10:45,092 --> 00:10:46,473
This week, it's homecoming.

228
00:10:46,507 --> 00:10:47,957
Whistle!

229
00:10:47,992 --> 00:10:49,683
Coach Larry Thomson
has, of late,

230
00:10:49,718 --> 00:10:52,410
imposed some order
and higher academic standards

231
00:10:52,444 --> 00:10:53,687
on the Knights.

232
00:10:53,722 --> 00:10:55,689
There are high hopes.

233
00:10:55,724 --> 00:10:57,415
♪

234
00:10:57,449 --> 00:10:58,927
Lord, thank you for this
food we're about to receive

235
00:10:58,934 --> 00:11:00,418
for the nourishment
of our bodies,

236
00:11:00,452 --> 00:11:02,385
and bless these young men
and these young women

237
00:11:02,420 --> 00:11:03,863
as they cheer
and as they play on the field.

238
00:11:03,870 --> 00:11:05,699
In Jesus name I pray, amen.

239
00:11:05,734 --> 00:11:07,874
Amen.

240
00:11:07,908 --> 00:11:09,565
Let's go eat, man.

241
00:11:09,599 --> 00:11:11,981
Local boosters put together
a pregame meal

242
00:11:12,016 --> 00:11:14,432
of ribs, baked potatoes,
and chicken.

243
00:11:14,466 --> 00:11:16,047
These kids, you know,
they got long days.

244
00:11:16,054 --> 00:11:18,919
They wake up 4:45 or 5:00,

245
00:11:18,954 --> 00:11:20,120
and they don't leave
off the hill with us

246
00:11:20,127 --> 00:11:21,715
until about 7:00
after practice,

247
00:11:21,750 --> 00:11:23,268
so, no, they go through a lot.

248
00:11:23,303 --> 00:11:26,755
How many generations of coal
in your family?

249
00:11:26,789 --> 00:11:29,033
- At least five.
- Wow.

250
00:11:29,067 --> 00:11:31,587
Coach Mike Anderson
is second in command.

251
00:11:31,621 --> 00:11:35,384
Coal in anybody else's family?
Yeah?

252
00:11:35,418 --> 00:11:38,870
Like, trash man, that's
a real common job in my family.

253
00:11:38,905 --> 00:11:40,354
Don't feel bad; trash men

254
00:11:40,389 --> 00:11:42,425
make more money
